WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:09.240
The Oxford Bookworms Library Stage 1 Sherlock Holmes and the Duke's

00:09.240 --> 00:17.480
Son by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle Text Adaptation by Jennifer Bassett

00:17.480 --> 00:26.840
Read by Richard Mitchley Copyright Oxford University Press 2002

00:26.840 --> 00:44.880
1 Sherlock Holmes has a visitor When visitors came to see Sherlock Holmes

00:44.880 --> 00:52.920
in Baker Street, they often did surprising things. Sometimes they put their heads in

00:52.920 --> 01:02.840
their hands and cried. Sometimes they talked and talked and couldn't stop. And sometimes

01:02.840 --> 01:11.800
they just sat there and didn't say a word. But nobody was more surprising than Dr. Thorny

01:11.800 --> 01:23.560
Croft Huxtable. He was a large man, tall, well dressed and important looking. He came

01:23.560 --> 01:33.960
into the room, walked to one of the big chairs and suddenly fell into it. He sat there with

01:33.960 --> 01:44.560
his eyes closed looking white and ill. I ran to get some water for him. Then I got my doctor's

01:44.560 --> 01:55.960
bag and looked at him carefully. What is it Watson? Said Holmes. He's all right, I think, I said.

01:55.960 --> 02:09.280
He's just very, very tired and probably hungry too. Holmes looked in the man's pockets and found a

02:09.280 --> 02:20.440
train ticket from Mackelton in the north of England. Mackelton, that's a long way, said Holmes. It's

02:20.480 --> 02:31.400
not twelve o'clock yet, so he probably left home before five o'clock this morning. After a minute

02:31.400 --> 02:42.640
or two, the man began to move and his eyes opened. A second later he got quickly to his feet. His

02:42.640 --> 02:53.480
face was now red and unhappy. Mr. Holmes, I am so sorry. I forgot to eat or drink anything this

02:53.480 --> 03:05.120
morning. That's why I felt ill. When you feel better, I began. I'm better now, thank you, said

03:05.120 --> 03:16.000
our visitor. And I want very much to talk to Mr. Holmes, to ask him something. Please, Mr. Holmes,

03:16.000 --> 03:27.280
come back to Mackelton with me by the next train. I'm sorry, that's not possible, said Holmes. I'm

03:27.360 --> 03:37.400
working on two important cases, the Ferris case and the Abigarveni case. I cannot leave London at

03:37.400 --> 03:49.400
the moment. Important cases, our visitor cried, but this case is very important too. You know

03:49.400 --> 03:58.160
about the kidnapping of the son of the Duke of Holderness three days ago? What? The government

03:58.160 --> 04:09.520
minister? Yes, that's him. So you didn't know. It's not in the newspapers yet, that's true. But

04:09.520 --> 04:18.440
Sherlock Holmes always hears news before other people, I thought. Holmes went to get one of his

04:18.440 --> 04:29.600
books and began to read the page about the Duke of Holderness. Holderness, Sixth Duke,

04:29.600 --> 04:43.800
wife, Edith, daughter of Lord Grey, one child, Lord Arthur Saltire, houses in London, Lancashire,

04:43.800 --> 04:57.440
and Wales. Government minister for this, for that, for the other. Well, well, said Holmes. He's

04:57.440 --> 05:07.320
one of the greatest men in the country. One of the greatest and one of the richest, said Dr.

05:07.400 --> 05:18.720
Huxtable. I know, Mr. Holmes, that you don't work for money. But I must tell you this, the Duke is

05:18.720 --> 05:29.720
offering five thousand pounds for news of his son, and another one thousand pounds for the name of

05:30.040 --> 05:40.960
his kidnapper. That, said Holmes, is a most interesting offer. He looked at me. What's

05:40.960 --> 05:48.440
it? I think we are going with Dr. Huxtable back to the north of England this afternoon.

05:49.440 --> 06:01.440
Holmes then looked at Dr. Huxtable. Now, sir, tell me everything. What happened? When did it

06:01.440 --> 06:12.200
happen? How did it happen? And why does Dr. Thornecraft Huxtable come to ask for my help three days

06:12.480 --> 06:26.920
later? Our visitor drank some water and began his story. Chapter two, Dr. Huxtable's story.

06:26.920 --> 06:47.920
My school, the priory school near Mackelton, is the best school for young boys in England.

06:48.920 --> 06:58.720
began Dr. Huxtable. We have the sons of Lord Son's, Lord Lever, and of many other important

06:58.720 --> 07:08.800
people. Three weeks ago, Mr. James Wilder, the Duke of Holderness' secretary, came to see me.

07:08.800 --> 07:17.800
The Duke, he said, wanted to send his son, the ten-year-old Lord Sultyre, to my school.

07:17.800 --> 07:29.480
On the first of May, young Lord Sultyre arrived. He's a nice boy, and he soon began to like school

07:29.480 --> 07:40.480
life, and to make friends. His life at home, you see, was not very happy. We all know about the

07:40.480 --> 07:49.600
Duke and his wife. The Duchess, of course, now lives in the south of France. She left the Duke

07:49.600 --> 07:59.600
about three months ago, I think. But the boy loved his mother, and was very unhappy when she left.

07:59.600 --> 08:10.600
Because of this, the Duke sent him to my school. And after two weeks with us, he was much happier.

08:11.600 --> 08:21.600
Then, on the night of the thirteenth of May, he disappeared. The way to his bedroom is through

08:21.600 --> 08:32.600
another larger room. Two older boys sleep there. One of them never sleeps very well, and he heard

08:32.600 --> 08:44.600
and saw nothing that night. So young Arthur did not go out through that room. His window was open,

08:44.600 --> 08:53.600
and there is ivy all up the wall of the house. It is easy to get out of the window and down the ivy

08:53.600 --> 09:05.600
to the ground. So we think that he went out that way. He was in his usual school things, we think,

09:05.600 --> 09:14.600
a short black coat and dark blue trousers. We looked all through his room very carefully,

09:14.600 --> 09:25.600
but we found nothing strange, nothing unusual. When I learnt the news at seven o'clock on Tuesday

09:25.600 --> 09:34.600
morning, I called everybody into the big school room. Then we learnt more bad news.

09:34.600 --> 09:44.600
Heidegger, the German teacher, was missing too. His room is not far from Arthur's room.

09:44.600 --> 09:55.600
Heidegger went down the ivy. We know this because we found his footprints on the ground under the window.

09:55.600 --> 10:05.600
We know too that he was only in his coat, trousers and shoes, because we found his shirt and his socks

10:05.600 --> 10:17.600
on the floor of his room. And he took his bicycle with him. Heidegger came to the school a year ago.

10:17.600 --> 10:25.600
He's a good teacher, but the boys don't like him because he isn't very friendly.

10:25.600 --> 10:36.600
So, Mr. Holmes, we have two missing people. It's now Thursday and there's still no news of them.

10:36.600 --> 10:42.600
Holmes took out a little notebook and began to write things down.

10:42.600 --> 10:46.600
The boy didn't go home, of course, he said.

10:46.600 --> 10:53.600
No, no. We asked at Holden's hall at once, said Dr. Huxtable.

10:53.600 --> 11:00.600
The Duke is very afraid for his son, and I am the unhappiest man in England.

11:00.600 --> 11:07.600
Mr. Holmes, you are a famous detective. Please help me.

11:07.600 --> 11:12.600
You make things very difficult for me, Holmes said.

11:12.600 --> 11:19.600
How can I find marks in the ivy or on the ground after three days?

11:19.600 --> 11:23.600
Why didn't you come to me at once?

11:23.600 --> 11:28.600
Because of the Duke, Dr. Huxtable said.

11:28.600 --> 11:34.600
He doesn't like people talking about his unhappy family life.

11:34.600 --> 11:37.600
And what are the police doing?

11:37.600 --> 11:46.600
Well, they heard about a boy and a young man at the station early on Tuesday.

11:46.600 --> 11:53.600
They looked for them, and last night they found them in Liverpool,

11:53.600 --> 11:58.600
but it was a man and his son going to visit a friend.

11:58.600 --> 12:06.600
We lost three days because of that, and last night I couldn't sleep.

12:06.600 --> 12:11.600
So I took the first train down to London this morning.

12:11.600 --> 12:17.600
Well, Dr. Huxtable, some more questions, said Holmes.

12:17.600 --> 12:22.600
Did the boy take German lessons? No.

12:22.600 --> 12:27.600
So he didn't know the German teacher well then.

12:27.600 --> 12:32.600
He probably never spoke to him, said Dr. Huxtable.

12:32.600 --> 12:35.600
Hmm, said Holmes.

12:35.600 --> 12:40.600
Does the boy have a bicycle? No.

12:40.600 --> 12:45.600
Was any other bicycle missing? No.

12:45.600 --> 12:54.600
So did the German teacher ride away on his bicycle in the night with the boy on his back?

12:54.600 --> 12:57.600
I don't think so.

12:57.600 --> 13:00.600
But what happened to the bicycle?

13:00.600 --> 13:04.600
Now, what about visitors?

13:04.600 --> 13:10.600
Did the boy have any visitors the day before? No.

13:10.600 --> 13:17.600
Did he get any letters? Yes, one letter from his father.

13:17.600 --> 13:23.600
Do you open the boy's letters, Dr. Huxtable? No.

13:23.600 --> 13:28.600
Then how do you know that the letter was from the father?

13:28.600 --> 13:35.600
I know the Duke's handwriting, and he says that he wrote a letter to his son.

13:35.600 --> 13:43.600
Did the boy get any letters from France? No. I never saw any.

13:43.600 --> 13:48.600
Do you understand me, Dr. Huxtable? Holmes said.

13:48.600 --> 13:55.600
Did someone take the boy away, or did the boy go freely?

13:55.600 --> 14:00.600
Because he had a letter from France, perhaps.

14:00.600 --> 14:04.600
I don't know, said Dr. Huxtable.

14:04.600 --> 14:09.600
He only had letters from his father, I think.

14:09.600 --> 14:14.600
Were father and son very friendly?

14:14.600 --> 14:21.600
The Duke is not a very friendly man, Mr. Holmes.

14:21.600 --> 14:30.600
He's not a bad father, but he is a government minister and has a lot of things to do.

14:30.600 --> 14:36.600
So the boy felt more friendly to his mother. Yes.

14:36.600 --> 14:42.600
Did he say that? No. Did the Duke tell you then?

14:42.600 --> 14:47.600
Oh, no. The Duke never talks about things like that.

14:47.600 --> 14:55.600
So how do you know? Mr. James Wilder, the Duke's secretary, told me.

14:55.600 --> 14:59.600
I see, said Holmes.

14:59.600 --> 15:04.600
That last letter of the Duke's, where is it now?

15:04.600 --> 15:08.600
The boy took it with him, Dr. Huxtable said.

15:08.600 --> 15:16.600
It's not in his room. Mr. Holmes, our train leaves in half an hour.

15:16.600 --> 15:20.600
Right, said Holmes. He looked at me.

15:20.600 --> 15:26.600
Watson, let's get ready and go off to the north with Dr. Huxtable.

15:26.600 --> 15:32.600
Perhaps we can find some answers to this mystery.

15:35.600 --> 15:41.600
Chapter 3, Holmes and Watson go north.

15:50.600 --> 16:00.600
It was dark when we arrived at Dr. Huxtable's famous school in the northern hills.

16:00.600 --> 16:05.600
We went quickly into the building out of the cold.

16:05.600 --> 16:13.600
And at once, someone ran up with news that Dr. Huxtable.

16:13.600 --> 16:16.600
He looked very surprised.

16:16.600 --> 16:20.600
The Duke is here, he told us.

16:20.600 --> 16:29.600
The Duke and Mr. Wilder, his secretary, are in my office and come and meet them.

16:30.600 --> 16:37.600
The government minister was a tall man with a long, thin face.

16:37.600 --> 16:43.600
He had red hair and a great red beard.

16:43.600 --> 16:48.600
He looked at us and did not smile.

16:48.600 --> 16:54.600
Next to him stood Mr. Wilder, a very young man.

16:55.600 --> 17:00.600
He was small with blue eyes and a watchful face.

17:00.600 --> 17:03.600
He spoke first.

17:03.600 --> 17:10.600
The Duke is surprised, Dr. Huxtable, to see Mr. Sherlock Holmes here.

17:10.600 --> 17:15.600
He doesn't want people to know about this.

17:15.600 --> 17:17.600
You know that.

17:17.600 --> 17:23.600
So why didn't you speak to the Duke before you went to London?

17:24.600 --> 17:28.600
But we need help, said Dr. Huxtable.

17:28.600 --> 17:29.600
And I...

17:29.600 --> 17:33.600
Well, said the Duke.

17:33.600 --> 17:40.600
Mr. Holmes is here now, and perhaps he can help us.

17:40.600 --> 17:43.600
He looked at Holmes.

17:43.600 --> 17:50.600
I'd like you to come and stay at Holden's Hall, Mr. Holmes.

17:50.600 --> 17:54.600
Thank you, sir, said Holmes.

17:54.600 --> 18:01.600
But I would like to stay near to the mystery, here at the school.

18:01.600 --> 18:05.600
Can I ask you one or two questions, perhaps?

18:05.600 --> 18:09.600
Of course, said the Duke.

18:09.600 --> 18:17.600
My questions are about the Duchess and about money, said Holmes.

18:17.600 --> 18:22.600
The Duchess knows nothing about this, said the Duke.

18:22.600 --> 18:27.600
And nobody is asking me for money.

18:27.600 --> 18:30.600
I see, said Holmes.

18:30.600 --> 18:36.600
You wrote a letter to your son before he disappeared.

18:36.600 --> 18:39.600
When did you post it?

18:39.600 --> 18:43.600
Post it, said Mr. Wilder angrily.

18:43.600 --> 18:47.600
The Duke does not post letters.

18:47.600 --> 18:55.600
I put the letter into the post bag with all the other letters that day.

18:55.600 --> 19:01.600
A minute or two later, the Duke and Mr. Wilder left.

19:01.600 --> 19:07.600
Holmes then began at once to work on the case.

19:07.600 --> 19:14.600
We looked carefully all through the boy's bedroom and the German teacher's room.

19:14.600 --> 19:24.600
We looked at the ivy on the wall, and we saw the footprints under the German teacher's window.

19:24.600 --> 19:28.600
But we learnt nothing new.

19:28.600 --> 19:36.600
Holmes then left the house and only came back after eleven o'clock.

19:36.600 --> 19:40.600
He had with him a large map.

19:40.600 --> 19:46.600
He brought it into my room and put it on the bed.

19:46.600 --> 19:52.600
This case is beginning to get interesting, Watson, he said.

19:52.600 --> 19:55.600
Look at this map.

19:55.600 --> 20:01.600
Here is the school, you see, and here is the road.

20:01.600 --> 20:08.600
So, did the boy and the teacher go along the road when they left?

20:08.600 --> 20:10.600
No, Watson.

20:10.600 --> 20:12.600
They did not.

20:12.600 --> 20:15.600
How do you know that, Holmes?

20:15.600 --> 20:17.600
I asked.

20:17.600 --> 20:26.600
Because there was a policeman here, look, he was there from midnight to six in the morning,

20:26.600 --> 20:30.600
and he saw nobody on the road.

20:30.600 --> 20:33.600
I spoke to him this evening.

20:33.600 --> 20:40.600
And here, at the other end, you see, is the white horse in.

20:40.600 --> 20:50.600
A woman there was ill, and the family watched the road all night, waiting for the doctor.

20:50.600 --> 20:58.600
The doctor didn't come until the morning, and the family saw nobody on the road.

20:58.600 --> 21:04.600
So, the boy and the teacher did not go by road.

21:04.600 --> 21:08.600
But Holmes, what about the bicycle?

21:08.600 --> 21:10.600
I asked.

21:10.600 --> 21:12.600
Yes, Watson.

21:12.600 --> 21:16.600
We must remember the bicycle, of course.

21:16.600 --> 21:21.600
But first, let's look to the south and the north.

21:21.600 --> 21:25.600
To the south, we have a big river.

21:25.600 --> 21:28.600
No bicycles there, then.

21:28.600 --> 21:35.600
And to the north, we have the trees, called ragged shore.

21:35.600 --> 21:41.600
And then a great moor, the lower gill moor.

21:41.600 --> 21:45.600
And here is Holderness Hall.

21:45.600 --> 21:54.600
16 kilometres from the school by road, but only nine kilometres across the moor.

21:54.600 --> 22:02.600
No other houses until the green man in along the Chesterfield Road.

22:02.600 --> 22:06.600
But the bicycle, I said again.

22:06.600 --> 22:10.600
Yes, yes, Watson, Holmes said.

22:10.600 --> 22:18.600
It is possible to ride a bicycle across the moor, difficult, but possible.

22:19.600 --> 22:24.600
Just then, Dr. Huxtable came quickly into the room.

22:24.600 --> 22:28.600
News, Mr. Holmes, he said excitedly.

22:28.600 --> 22:31.600
I bring news.

22:31.600 --> 22:35.600
In his hands was a blue school hat.

22:35.600 --> 22:39.600
Look, this is the boy's hat.

22:39.600 --> 22:43.600
One of my gardeners found it this evening.

22:44.600 --> 22:48.600
Where, man, where? asked Holmes.

22:48.600 --> 22:53.600
Just north of ragged shore, said Dr. Huxtable.

22:53.600 --> 22:56.600
Aha, said Holmes.

22:56.600 --> 22:59.600
What did I tell you, Watson?

22:59.600 --> 23:07.600
Tomorrow, we must walk north across the moor.

23:07.600 --> 23:21.600
Chapter 4, The Body On The Moor.

23:21.600 --> 23:30.600
Very early the next morning, I opened my eyes and saw Holmes next to my bed.

23:30.600 --> 23:33.600
He was already dressed.

23:33.600 --> 23:36.600
Come, Watson, he cried.

23:36.600 --> 23:39.600
There is hot coffee ready for you.

23:39.600 --> 23:43.600
We leave in ten minutes.

23:43.600 --> 23:47.600
By six o'clock, we were through ragged shore.

23:47.600 --> 23:53.600
And half an hour later, we were on lower gill moor.

23:53.600 --> 23:58.600
Across the middle of the moor was a small river.

23:58.600 --> 24:04.600
And the ground all around it was very wet.

24:04.600 --> 24:10.600
We can easily see tracks in this wet ground, said Holmes.

24:10.600 --> 24:14.600
Look carefully, Watson.

24:14.600 --> 24:21.600
We moved slowly across the moor, looking at every centimetre of mud.

24:21.600 --> 24:31.600
We found hundreds of sheep tracks, and once some cow tracks, but no bicycle tracks.

24:31.600 --> 24:36.600
And then, at last, we found something.

24:36.600 --> 24:46.600
Not far from the little river, right across some nice black mud was the track of a bicycle.

24:46.600 --> 24:50.600
Hoorah! I cried. We have it.

24:50.600 --> 24:54.600
But Holmes did not look happy.

24:54.600 --> 25:00.600
It's a bicycle, yes, but not the bicycle.

25:00.600 --> 25:04.600
Every bicycle has different tires.

25:04.600 --> 25:09.600
I know forty-two different kinds of tire.

25:09.600 --> 25:16.600
This tire is a Dunlop, but Heidegger's bicycle had Palmer tires.

25:16.600 --> 25:19.600
The English teacher told me that.

25:19.600 --> 25:22.600
So this is not Heidegger.

25:22.600 --> 25:25.600
Is it the boy then?

25:25.600 --> 25:28.600
I asked. Probably not.

25:28.600 --> 25:34.600
The boy didn't take a bicycle with him, said Holmes.

25:34.600 --> 25:38.600
He looked again at the track in the mud.

25:38.600 --> 25:42.600
This track is going away from the school.

25:42.600 --> 25:46.600
Or perhaps to the school, I said.

25:46.600 --> 25:49.600
No, no, my dear Watson.

25:49.600 --> 25:52.600
Look at the tracks of the two tires.

25:52.600 --> 25:55.600
Are they the same?

25:55.600 --> 25:58.600
Erm, no, I said.

25:58.600 --> 26:02.600
One tire makes a deeper track.

26:02.600 --> 26:06.600
And that's the back wheel, said Holmes.

26:06.600 --> 26:11.600
Because the rider, of course, sits over the back wheel.

26:11.600 --> 26:16.600
The deeper track is the one on top.

26:16.600 --> 26:23.600
So this bicycle went that way, across the moor, away from the school.

26:23.600 --> 26:26.600
But who was the rider?

26:26.600 --> 26:29.600
Where did he come from?

26:29.600 --> 26:35.600
We followed the Dunlop track back, nearly to ragged shore.

26:35.600 --> 26:39.600
Then we lost it in some cow tracks.

26:39.600 --> 26:45.600
Holmes sat down and thought for some minutes.

26:45.600 --> 26:48.600
Nope, he said, getting up.

26:48.600 --> 26:51.600
We must leave this question for now.

26:51.600 --> 26:56.600
Back to the mud by the river, Watson.

26:56.600 --> 27:00.600
Two hours later, Holmes gave a happy cry.

27:00.600 --> 27:09.600
I quickly ran over to him and looked down at a long, thin track in the mud.

27:09.600 --> 27:12.600
It was the Palmer tire.

27:12.600 --> 27:16.600
Here is Heidegger, cried Holmes.

27:16.600 --> 27:20.600
Let's follow him, Watson.

27:20.600 --> 27:27.600
For a kilometer or more, we followed the Palmer tire north across the moor,

27:27.600 --> 27:33.600
losing the track, finding it again, losing it and finding it.

27:33.600 --> 27:37.600
Suddenly, the track stopped.

27:37.600 --> 27:39.600
What happened here?

27:39.600 --> 27:43.600
I said, did he fall?

27:43.600 --> 27:47.600
Holmes looked carefully on the ground.

27:47.600 --> 27:52.600
Then he moved to some small bushes with yellow flowers on them.

27:52.600 --> 27:56.600
Look, he said quietly.

27:56.600 --> 28:06.600
On one of the yellow flowers, there was something red, the dark brownie red of blood.

28:06.600 --> 28:09.600
Bad, said Holmes.

28:09.600 --> 28:11.600
Bad.

28:11.600 --> 28:13.600
What do I read here?

28:13.600 --> 28:17.600
Something or someone hit him.

28:17.600 --> 28:18.600
He fell.

28:18.600 --> 28:20.600
He stood up.

28:20.600 --> 28:25.600
He got onto his bicycle again and rode away.

28:25.600 --> 28:29.600
But there is no other track.

28:29.600 --> 28:34.600
Some cow tracks here, but no footprints.

28:34.600 --> 28:38.600
We must follow the blood, Watson.

28:38.600 --> 28:41.600
We soon found the bicycle.

28:41.600 --> 28:48.600
And then, behind a bush, we saw a shoe and found a body.

28:48.600 --> 28:56.600
There was blood on the man's head and face, and he was very, very dead.

28:56.600 --> 29:00.600
He had shoes on, but no socks.

29:00.600 --> 29:04.600
And we saw a night shirt under his open coat.

29:04.600 --> 29:08.600
It was the German teacher.

29:08.600 --> 29:12.600
Poor man, Holmes said quietly.

29:12.600 --> 29:15.600
What shall we do, Watson?

29:15.600 --> 29:18.600
We can't lose any more time.

29:18.600 --> 29:23.600
But we must tell someone about this poor man.

29:23.600 --> 29:26.600
Shall I run back to the school?

29:26.600 --> 29:28.600
I said.

29:28.600 --> 29:33.600
No, I need you with me.

29:33.600 --> 29:37.600
Holmes stood up and looked around.

29:37.600 --> 29:40.600
Look, he said.

29:40.600 --> 29:43.600
There's a workman over there.

29:43.600 --> 29:48.600
He can go back to the school for us.

29:48.600 --> 29:57.600
I went and got the workman, and Holmes wrote a note for Dr. Huxtable.

29:57.600 --> 30:08.600
The poor workman took one look at the body and began to run quickly down the hill to ragged shore.

30:08.600 --> 30:18.600
Now, said Holmes, before we go on, let's think carefully for a minute.

30:18.600 --> 30:21.600
What do we know so far?

30:21.600 --> 30:26.600
First, the boy left freely.

30:26.600 --> 30:28.600
He was dressed.

30:28.600 --> 30:31.600
He did not leave suddenly.

30:31.600 --> 30:33.600
He wanted to go.

30:33.600 --> 30:36.600
Perhaps with someone?

30:36.600 --> 30:38.600
Perhaps not.

30:38.600 --> 30:46.600
But the German teacher left without his socks and without his shirt.

30:46.600 --> 30:50.600
So he left very suddenly.

30:50.600 --> 30:53.600
That's right, I said.

30:53.600 --> 30:57.600
And why did Heidegger go?

30:57.600 --> 31:03.600
Because, from his bedroom window, he saw the boy.

31:03.600 --> 31:08.600
Because he wanted to follow him and bring him back.

31:08.600 --> 31:12.600
So far, so good.

31:12.600 --> 31:18.600
But why doesn't Heidegger just run after the boy?

31:18.600 --> 31:23.600
A man can easily run faster than a boy.

31:23.600 --> 31:27.600
But Heidegger doesn't do this.

31:27.600 --> 31:30.600
He gets his bicycle.

31:30.600 --> 31:34.600
He knows that he needs his bicycle.

31:34.600 --> 31:36.600
Why?

31:36.600 --> 31:39.600
Ah, I said.

31:39.600 --> 31:42.600
Because the boy has a bicycle.

31:42.600 --> 31:45.600
Not so fast, Watson.

31:45.600 --> 31:48.600
Think about it.

31:48.600 --> 31:53.600
Heidegger dies eight kilometers from the school.

31:53.600 --> 31:58.600
So the boy is moving very fast.

31:58.600 --> 32:06.600
Because it is eight kilometers before a man on a bicycle can get near him.

32:06.600 --> 32:14.600
And Heidegger dies because someone hits him very hard on the head.

32:14.600 --> 32:17.600
A boy can't do that.

32:17.600 --> 32:21.600
So there was someone with the boy.

32:21.600 --> 32:25.600
A man, let's say.

32:25.600 --> 32:32.600
But we looked very carefully at the mud all round poor Heidegger's body, Watson.

32:32.600 --> 32:35.600
And what did we find?

32:35.600 --> 32:39.600
Some cow tracks, but nothing more.

32:39.600 --> 32:42.600
No footprints from people.

32:42.600 --> 32:45.600
No bicycle tracks.

32:45.600 --> 32:48.600
Homes, I cried.

32:48.600 --> 32:51.600
This is not possible.

32:51.600 --> 32:54.600
Very good, Watson, he said.

32:54.600 --> 32:57.600
It's not possible.

32:57.600 --> 33:01.600
So something is wrong with my thinking.

33:01.600 --> 33:04.600
What can it be?

33:04.600 --> 33:10.600
Perhaps, I said, Heidegger broke his head in a fall.

33:10.600 --> 33:13.600
In mud, Watson.

33:13.600 --> 33:17.600
Oh, I don't know. I just don't know.

33:17.600 --> 33:19.600
Come, come, Watson.

33:19.600 --> 33:21.600
Said homes.

33:21.600 --> 33:25.600
Every mystery has an answer.

33:25.600 --> 33:31.600
But for now, the Palmer tyre can tell us nothing more.

33:31.600 --> 33:37.600
So we must go back to the Dunlop tyre.

33:37.600 --> 33:43.600
We found the Dunlop track again, and followed it north.

33:43.600 --> 33:49.600
Here there was very little mud, and we lost the track.

33:49.600 --> 33:58.600
Across the moor, we could now see Holderness Hall, some kilometres to our left.

33:58.600 --> 34:04.600
And in front of us, we could see the Chesterfield Road.

34:04.600 --> 34:12.600
We walked down to the road, and along to the Green Man Inn.

34:12.600 --> 34:14.600
Chapter 5.

34:14.600 --> 34:18.600
A Visit to the Green Man.

34:28.600 --> 34:33.600
When we were near the Inn, homes suddenly cried out.

34:33.600 --> 34:40.600
Ah! My foot! I can't stand on it. Help me, Watson.

34:40.600 --> 34:47.600
I took his arm, and we walked slowly to the door of the Inn.

34:47.600 --> 34:53.600
A man stood there, smoking, and watching us.

34:53.600 --> 34:59.600
How are you, Mr. Ruben Hayes? Said homes.

34:59.600 --> 35:05.600
Who are you? And how do you know my name? Said the man.

35:05.600 --> 35:08.600
He looked very unfriendly.

35:08.600 --> 35:13.600
Because it's on the door of the Inn, over your head.

35:13.600 --> 35:15.600
Said homes.

35:15.600 --> 35:18.600
But can you help me, Mr. Hayes?

35:18.600 --> 35:21.600
No, I can't.

35:21.600 --> 35:27.600
But I need help. I can't put my foot to the ground.

35:27.600 --> 35:31.600
Well, don't put it to the ground.

35:31.600 --> 35:33.600
Home smiled.

35:33.600 --> 35:36.600
Look, he said.

35:36.600 --> 35:44.600
It's very important, and I can offer you a pound for the use of a bicycle.

35:44.600 --> 35:47.600
Where do you want to go?

35:47.600 --> 35:49.600
Asked Mr. Hayes.

35:49.600 --> 35:52.600
To Holderness Hall.

35:53.600 --> 35:57.600
Oh! Friends of the Duke, are you?

35:57.600 --> 36:03.600
Mr. Hayes laughed, looking at our muddy shoes and trousers.

36:03.600 --> 36:06.600
Homes laughed, too.

36:06.600 --> 36:12.600
Well, we are bringing him news of his lost son, he said.

36:12.600 --> 36:16.600
The boy is in Liverpool.

36:16.600 --> 36:20.600
Mr. Hayes's face went white, then red.

36:21.600 --> 36:24.600
Oh! He said carefully.

36:24.600 --> 36:28.600
That's, erm, that's good news.

36:28.600 --> 36:35.600
I worked for the Duke once, but he wasn't good to me.

36:35.600 --> 36:41.600
I don't like him, but I'm pleased about the boy.

36:41.600 --> 36:44.600
We all went into the Inn.

36:45.600 --> 36:50.600
Now, said Holmes, something to eat first, please.

36:50.600 --> 36:54.600
Then you can bring round the bicycle.

36:54.600 --> 36:59.600
I haven't got a bicycle, said Mr. Hayes.

36:59.600 --> 37:04.600
Homes put a pound on the table.

37:04.600 --> 37:09.600
I tell you, man, that I haven't got a bicycle.

37:09.600 --> 37:13.600
You can have two horses to take you to the hall.

37:13.600 --> 37:18.600
He brought us something to eat, and we ate hungry.

37:18.600 --> 37:25.600
Through the window, we could see the stables at the back of the Inn.

37:25.600 --> 37:36.600
Once Holmes got up and walked round the room, then stood, looking out of the window at the stables.

37:36.600 --> 37:42.600
Surprisingly, his foot was now very much better.

37:42.600 --> 37:46.600
Suddenly, he laughed and looked at me.

37:46.600 --> 37:49.600
I've got it, he cried.

37:49.600 --> 37:53.600
Yes, of course. That's it.

37:53.600 --> 37:58.600
Watson, did you see any cow tracks today?

37:58.600 --> 38:04.600
Yes, I said. Lots of them, everywhere.

38:04.600 --> 38:09.600
And how many cows did you see on the moor?

38:09.600 --> 38:13.600
I don't remember any, I said.

38:13.600 --> 38:17.600
Isn't that strange, Watson?

38:17.600 --> 38:22.600
Lots of cow tracks, but no cows.

38:22.600 --> 38:27.600
And do you remember those tracks, Watson?

38:27.600 --> 38:30.600
He took out his notebook.

38:30.600 --> 38:37.600
There were tracks like this, and sometimes like this.

38:37.600 --> 38:41.600
Do you remember that, Watson?

38:41.600 --> 38:43.600
No, I don't.

38:43.600 --> 38:47.600
I said, what does it mean, Holmes?

38:47.600 --> 38:53.600
It means that it's a very strange cow, Watson.

38:53.600 --> 38:57.600
Cows don't move like that.

38:57.600 --> 39:04.600
Now, let's go quietly out and have a look around these tracks.

39:04.600 --> 39:08.600
There were two tired-looking horses in the stables.

39:08.600 --> 39:14.600
Holmes looked carefully at one of the horses' feet and laughed.

39:14.600 --> 39:20.600
Look, Watson, old shoes, but new nails.

39:20.600 --> 39:27.600
Oh, this case gets more interesting every minute.

39:28.600 --> 39:31.600
I began to ask Holmes a question.

39:31.600 --> 39:35.600
But suddenly we heard someone behind us.

39:35.600 --> 39:39.600
And there was Mr. Ruben Hayes.

39:39.600 --> 39:43.600
His face was red and angry.

39:43.600 --> 39:46.600
What are you doing in my stables?

39:46.600 --> 39:48.600
He cried.

39:48.600 --> 39:51.600
We're just looking at him.

39:51.600 --> 39:54.600
What are you doing in my stables?

39:54.600 --> 39:56.600
He cried.

39:56.600 --> 40:02.600
We're just looking at your horses, Mr. Hayes, said Holmes, smiling.

40:02.600 --> 40:07.600
Why, are you afraid of something?

40:07.600 --> 40:12.600
The man opened his mouth, then closed it quickly.

40:12.600 --> 40:17.600
His face was still red and angry.

40:17.600 --> 40:21.600
Holmes did not give him time to speak.

40:21.600 --> 40:26.600
I think your horses are tired, Mr. Hayes.

40:26.600 --> 40:28.600
We can walk to the hall.

40:28.600 --> 40:31.600
It's not far.

40:31.600 --> 40:36.600
Three kilometers by the road, Mr. Hayes said.

40:36.600 --> 40:41.600
His eyes still watched us angrily.

40:41.600 --> 40:45.600
It was nearly dark when we left.

40:45.600 --> 40:50.600
We walked along the road for about 100 meters.

40:50.600 --> 40:53.600
Then Holmes took my arm.

40:53.600 --> 40:55.600
Quick, Watson.

40:55.600 --> 40:58.600
Off the road and up the hill.

40:58.600 --> 41:04.600
Then we can come down the hill at the back of the inn.

41:04.600 --> 41:07.600
We ran up the hill.

41:07.600 --> 41:11.600
This man Hayes, I said,

41:11.600 --> 41:15.600
he knows all about the kidnapping.

41:15.600 --> 41:17.600
Is that right, Holmes?

41:17.600 --> 41:20.600
Of course it is, he said.

41:20.600 --> 41:25.600
We can learn a lot more from Mr. Hayes.

41:25.600 --> 41:28.600
Ah, who's this?

41:28.600 --> 41:31.600
Watson, get down.

41:31.600 --> 41:35.600
There was a bicycle on the road.

41:35.600 --> 41:38.600
It came past us very quickly.

41:38.600 --> 41:40.600
And we saw the rider.

41:40.600 --> 41:45.600
Mr. James Wilder, the Duke secretary.

41:45.600 --> 41:49.600
His face was white and afraid.

41:49.600 --> 41:52.600
Quick, Watson, said Holmes.

41:52.600 --> 41:55.600
We must watch him.

41:55.600 --> 42:02.600
We ran down the hill and stopped when we could see the back door of the inn.

42:02.600 --> 42:07.600
Wilder's bicycle was by the wall near the door.

42:08.600 --> 42:11.600
For five minutes nothing happened.

42:11.600 --> 42:21.600
Then a man on a horse rode quickly out of the stables and disappeared down the road.

42:21.600 --> 42:24.600
What do you think of that, Watson?

42:24.600 --> 42:26.600
Said Holmes.

42:26.600 --> 42:28.600
Somebody's running away.

42:28.600 --> 42:36.600
Yes, but not James Wilder, because there he is at the door.

42:37.600 --> 42:41.600
We could see Wilder in the light from the door.

42:41.600 --> 42:44.600
He stood there looking out.

42:44.600 --> 42:52.600
And ten minutes later another man came down the road and went into the inn.

42:52.600 --> 42:57.600
Then a light came on in a room upstairs.

42:57.600 --> 42:59.600
Come, Watson.

42:59.600 --> 43:04.600
We must get nearer, Holmes said.

43:04.600 --> 43:12.600
We went down the hill and walked very quietly to the back door of the inn.

43:12.600 --> 43:16.600
The bicycle was still by the wall.

43:16.600 --> 43:21.600
Holmes looked at the wheel and laughed quietly.

43:21.600 --> 43:25.600
A Dunlop tire, Watson.

43:25.600 --> 43:30.600
Now, I must look through that upstairs window.

43:30.600 --> 43:34.600
So I need your back, Watson.

43:34.600 --> 43:41.600
Holmes stood on my back, but only for a second, and then he was down again.

43:41.600 --> 43:44.600
Come, my friend, he said.

43:44.600 --> 43:50.600
It's a long walk to the school, so let's start at once.

43:50.600 --> 43:56.600
I can give you all the answers to this mystery tomorrow.

43:56.600 --> 44:01.600
It was a long, cold, muddy walk back to the school.

44:01.600 --> 44:04.600
I went to bed at once.

44:04.600 --> 44:09.600
But Holmes went out again to Mackelton, I think.

44:09.600 --> 44:19.600
I was very tired and slept all night like a dead man.

44:19.600 --> 44:22.600
Chapter 6

44:22.600 --> 44:29.600
Sherlock Holmes talks to the Duke.

44:29.600 --> 44:39.600
At eleven o'clock the next morning,

44:39.600 --> 44:45.600
Holmes and I were in the Duke's office at Holden S Hall.

44:45.600 --> 44:49.600
Mr. Wilder came to speak to us.

44:49.600 --> 44:55.600
The Duke can see no one today, he said to Holmes.

44:55.600 --> 44:58.600
Holmes looked at him coldly.

44:58.600 --> 45:02.600
The Duke can see me, he said.

45:02.600 --> 45:06.600
Please tell him that I am here.

45:06.600 --> 45:12.600
After half an hour, the Duke of Holden S came into the room.

45:12.600 --> 45:16.600
He looked older, tired and ill.

45:16.600 --> 45:20.600
Well, Mr. Holmes, he said.

45:20.600 --> 45:24.600
Holmes looked at James Wilder.

45:24.600 --> 45:31.600
I can speak more freely without your secretary here, sir.

45:31.600 --> 45:34.600
Very well, said the Duke tiredly.

45:34.600 --> 45:37.600
Please, James.

45:37.600 --> 45:41.600
James Wilder gave Holmes an angry look.

45:41.600 --> 45:46.600
But he went out of the room and shut the door.

45:46.600 --> 45:50.600
Holmes looked at the Duke.

45:50.600 --> 45:57.600
You are offering, I hear, five thousand pounds for news of your son.

45:57.600 --> 45:59.600
True.

45:59.600 --> 46:05.600
And another thousand pounds for the name of the kidnapper.

46:05.600 --> 46:07.600
True.

46:07.600 --> 46:10.600
My friends smiled.

46:10.600 --> 46:14.600
I see your checkbook on the table, sir.

46:14.600 --> 46:20.600
I would like to have your check for six thousand pounds.

46:20.600 --> 46:25.600
Mr. Sherlock Holmes, the Duke said angrily.

46:25.600 --> 46:28.600
What is this about?

46:28.600 --> 46:32.600
Do you have news of my son or not?

46:32.600 --> 46:36.600
Oh, yes, said Holmes.

46:36.600 --> 46:40.600
The Duke's eyes never left Holmes's face.

46:40.600 --> 46:43.600
Where is my son?

46:43.600 --> 46:45.600
He said quietly.

46:45.600 --> 46:56.600
He is, or was, last night, at the Green Man Inn, three kilometres along the road to Chesterfield.

46:56.600 --> 47:00.600
The Duke fell back in his chair.

47:00.600 --> 47:04.600
And the name of the kidnapper?

47:04.600 --> 47:08.600
Sherlock Holmes's answer was a very surprising one.

47:08.600 --> 47:11.600
You, he said.

47:11.600 --> 47:15.600
And now, sir, your check, please.

47:15.600 --> 47:20.600
The Duke stood up, his face white and angry.

47:20.600 --> 47:26.600
Then he sat down again and put his face in his hands.

47:26.600 --> 47:31.600
It was some minutes before he spoke.

47:31.600 --> 47:33.600
How much do you know?

47:33.600 --> 47:35.600
He asked.

47:35.600 --> 47:40.600
I saw you with him last night, said Holmes.

47:40.600 --> 47:44.600
And how many people know about this?

47:44.600 --> 47:49.600
Only I and my friend here, Dr. Watson.

47:49.600 --> 47:56.600
The Duke took out a pen, opened his checkbook, and began to write.

47:57.600 --> 48:01.600
When I made this offer, I didn't know.

48:01.600 --> 48:05.600
He stopped, then began again.

48:05.600 --> 48:11.600
Are you and your friend going to talk about this, Mr. Holmes?

48:11.600 --> 48:16.600
I don't understand you, sir, said Holmes.

48:16.600 --> 48:24.600
I mean, nobody needs to know about this little family mystery.

48:24.600 --> 48:28.600
Just you and your friend Watson.

48:28.600 --> 48:35.600
Look, here is my check for 12,000 pounds.

48:35.600 --> 48:40.600
Holmes gave him a cold little smile.

48:40.600 --> 48:42.600
I'm sorry, sir.

48:42.600 --> 48:47.600
There is a dead man in this case, you remember?

48:47.600 --> 48:51.600
But that wasn't James, cried the Duke.

48:51.600 --> 48:54.600
He knew nothing about it.

48:54.600 --> 49:01.600
He was very, very unhappy when he heard about the killing.

49:01.600 --> 49:04.600
Murder, said Holmes.

49:04.600 --> 49:08.600
But James wasn't there.

49:08.600 --> 49:15.600
And when he heard about it, he came to me at once and told me everything.

49:16.600 --> 49:19.600
Oh, Mr. Holmes, you must help him.

49:19.600 --> 49:21.600
You must.

49:21.600 --> 49:24.600
He is not the murderer.

49:24.600 --> 49:28.600
The murderer ran away last night.

49:28.600 --> 49:32.600
Holmes smiled again.

49:32.600 --> 49:36.600
I have a little more news for you, sir.

49:36.600 --> 49:43.600
The police met Mr. Ruben Hayes last night at Chesterfield Station.

49:43.600 --> 49:49.600
Mr. Hayes is not running anywhere for a very long time.

49:49.600 --> 49:54.600
The Duke looked at Holmes with an open mouth.

49:54.600 --> 49:59.600
You know everything, he said.

49:59.600 --> 50:02.600
But I am pleased to hear about Hayes.

50:02.600 --> 50:06.600
He was always a bad man.

50:06.600 --> 50:10.600
And that news can only help James.

50:10.600 --> 50:14.600
James, your secretary, said Holmes.

50:14.600 --> 50:16.600
No, sir.

50:16.600 --> 50:18.600
My son.

50:18.600 --> 50:21.600
James Wilder is my son.

50:25.600 --> 50:29.600
Chapter 7, The Duke's Son.

50:29.600 --> 50:47.600
When the Duke said this, I was very surprised, but Holmes was surprised too.

50:47.600 --> 50:51.600
This is news to me, he said.

50:51.600 --> 50:54.600
Can you tell me more?

50:54.600 --> 51:00.600
The Duke stood up and walked round the room for a minute.

51:00.600 --> 51:04.600
I must tell you everything, he said.

51:04.600 --> 51:08.600
I didn't want to talk about it, but I must.

51:08.600 --> 51:11.600
I see that now.

51:11.600 --> 51:16.600
He sat down again and began his story.

51:16.600 --> 51:22.600
When I was a young man, Mr. Holmes, I was in love.

51:22.600 --> 51:26.600
No, so much in love.

51:26.600 --> 51:34.600
It only happens to you once, and this woman was the love of my life.

51:34.600 --> 51:40.600
I wanted her to be my wife, but she died.

51:40.600 --> 51:47.600
She left me this one child, and I loved him because of her.

51:47.600 --> 51:57.600
When I look in his face, I see her, and remember her, and can't stop loving her.

51:57.600 --> 52:01.600
I must have the boy near me because of this.

52:01.600 --> 52:09.600
But a government minister cannot tell the world about a love child like this.

52:09.600 --> 52:17.600
So, to the world, James is my young secretary, not my son.

52:17.600 --> 52:21.600
He knows that I am his father.

52:21.600 --> 52:26.600
He hates the Duchess because she is not his mother.

52:26.600 --> 52:33.600
And he hates my younger son, Arthur, because Arthur has everything.

52:33.600 --> 52:41.600
Arthur has a name, a famous father, houses, money, everything.

52:41.600 --> 52:45.600
James has nothing.

52:45.600 --> 52:57.600
Well, he has some money, of course, but he is just Mr. James Wilder, and he wants to be the Duke of Holderness one day.

52:57.600 --> 53:01.600
That's not possible, of course.

53:01.600 --> 53:05.600
But James can't understand that.

53:05.600 --> 53:10.600
And so, you see, I was afraid for Arthur.

53:10.600 --> 53:16.600
And that's why I sent him to Dr. Huxtable's school.

53:16.600 --> 53:20.600
And what does James do next?

53:20.600 --> 53:23.600
He kidnaps my poor Arthur.

53:23.600 --> 53:28.600
It changes nothing, but James can't see that.

53:28.600 --> 53:35.600
He wants me to say, yes, James, now you can be my first son.

53:35.600 --> 53:38.600
You can have everything.

53:38.600 --> 53:42.600
Arthur can be the number two son.

53:42.600 --> 53:47.600
But I can't do that. Of course I can't.

53:47.600 --> 53:55.600
James knew this man haze, you see, because haze worked for me once.

53:55.600 --> 54:02.600
James asked for haze's help, and the man was happy to do it.

54:02.600 --> 54:07.600
You remember my letter to Arthur on that last day?

54:07.600 --> 54:14.600
Well, James opened the letter and put in a note from him.

54:14.600 --> 54:21.600
That evening, he cycled across the moor and met Arthur in ragged shore.

54:21.600 --> 54:25.600
He talked about the Duchess, Arthur's mother.

54:25.600 --> 54:29.600
She wants to see you, he told Arthur.

54:29.600 --> 54:32.600
She's waiting on the moor.

54:32.600 --> 54:38.600
Come back at midnight, and a man with a horse can take you to her.

54:38.600 --> 54:45.600
Of course, poor Arthur wanted to see his mother, so he came.

54:45.600 --> 54:51.600
Haze was there with two horses, and they rode across the moor.

54:51.600 --> 54:57.600
But the German teacher followed them, and haze killed him.

54:57.600 --> 55:02.600
Haze then took Arthur to the green man.

55:02.600 --> 55:09.600
Well, Mr. Holmes, I knew nothing about any of this until the murder.

55:10.600 --> 55:15.600
James is a bad boy, but he does not murder people.

55:15.600 --> 55:21.600
When he heard the news, he came to me at once, crying.

55:21.600 --> 55:23.600
What could I do?

55:23.600 --> 55:27.600
I didn't want the world to know about this.

55:27.600 --> 55:31.600
So James went down to the green man.

55:31.600 --> 55:37.600
He told Haze to run away, because everybody knew about the murder now,

55:37.600 --> 55:41.600
and knew the murderer's name, too.

55:41.600 --> 55:44.600
Haze left at once.

55:44.600 --> 55:48.600
Later, I went down and saw Arthur.

55:48.600 --> 55:56.600
I left him there with Mrs. Haze, because I couldn't say anything to the police just then.

55:56.600 --> 56:01.600
So, Mr. Holmes, now you know everything.

56:02.600 --> 56:05.600
Hmm, said Holmes.

56:05.600 --> 56:07.600
You help a murderer.

56:07.600 --> 56:09.600
You say nothing to the police.

56:09.600 --> 56:17.600
You leave your young son in a dirty inn, and you ask for my help.

56:17.600 --> 56:22.600
People never spoke to the Duke of Holderness like this, usually.

56:22.600 --> 56:26.600
His face was red, but he said nothing.

56:26.600 --> 56:31.600
First, said Holmes, we must bring Arthur home.

56:31.600 --> 56:36.600
Yes, the Duke said quietly.

56:36.600 --> 56:41.600
Holmes quickly wrote a note and took it out of the room.

56:41.600 --> 56:45.600
A minute later, he was back.

56:45.600 --> 56:52.600
Now, what are you going to do about Mr. James Wilder, he said?

56:52.600 --> 56:56.600
I understand you, Mr. Holmes, said the Duke.

56:56.600 --> 57:01.600
James is leaving me and going to Australia next week.

57:01.600 --> 57:04.600
Good, said Holmes.

57:04.600 --> 57:06.600
And the Duchess?

57:06.600 --> 57:11.600
Perhaps without James in the house, you and she...

57:11.600 --> 57:16.600
Yes, I wrote to the Duchess this morning.

57:16.600 --> 57:18.600
Holmes stood up.

57:18.600 --> 57:23.600
Well, he said, Watson and I can go home now, I think.

57:23.600 --> 57:28.600
There is just one other small thing.

57:28.600 --> 57:33.600
This man haze took two horses across the moor,

57:33.600 --> 57:39.600
but the horses' feet made the tracks of a cow in the mud.

57:39.600 --> 57:42.600
How was this possible?

57:42.600 --> 57:47.600
The Duke looked surprised and thought for a minute.

57:47.600 --> 57:52.600
Then he went away and came back two minutes later,

57:52.600 --> 57:56.600
with a glass box in his hands.

57:56.600 --> 58:00.600
In the box were some horse shoes.

58:00.600 --> 58:06.600
We found these shoes under the ground in the garden, the Duke said.

58:06.600 --> 58:11.600
They are about five hundred years old, we think.

58:11.600 --> 58:17.600
The Holdeness family has a long and interesting past.

58:17.600 --> 58:22.600
Holmes opened the box and took out one shoe.

58:22.600 --> 58:30.600
It was a shoe for a horse's foot, but it looked like a cloven cow's foot.

58:30.600 --> 58:36.600
Holmes wet his finger and ran it round the bottom of the shoe.

58:36.600 --> 58:40.600
A little mud came off on his finger.

58:40.600 --> 58:43.600
Thank you, said Holmes.

58:43.600 --> 58:46.600
He put the horse shoe back in its box.

58:46.600 --> 58:53.600
That shoe is the second most interesting thing in the north of England, he said.

58:53.600 --> 58:57.600
And the first asked the Duke.

58:57.600 --> 59:02.600
Holmes took the check for twelve thousand pounds from the table

59:02.600 --> 59:06.600
and slowly put it into his notebook.

59:06.600 --> 59:10.600
I am a poor man, he said.

59:10.600 --> 59:17.600
He looked lovingly at the notebook, then put it carefully in his pocket.

